{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1944"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1944"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.52,0.16,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department three days after an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy with confusion and lethargy. Her partner reports she has been increasingly drowsy since discharge yesterday and had one episode of vomiting this morning. She has a recent diagnosis of major depressive disorder and no other significant medical history. Her only medication is paroxetine daily, which she started three weeks ago. She does not smoke and drinks four standard drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy but rousable. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. She has moist mucous membranes, a central capillary refill time of two seconds, normal skin turgor, and no peripheral oedema. Her Glasgow Coma Scale is 14 (E4, V4, M6). Cardiorespiratory and abdominal examinations are unremarkable. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 118 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 92 mmol/L (95-105)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-6.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 23 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 4.8 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 68 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum osmolality 242 mOsm/kg (275-295)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine sodium 55 mmol/L (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine osmolality 380 mOsm/kg (\u0026lt;100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid function tests within reference limits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMorning cortisol within reference limits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluid restriction to 800mL/day","Intravenous 3% hypertonic saline","Intravenous 0.9% normal saline","Oral sodium chloride tablets","Intravenous hydrocortisone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe symptomatic hyponatraemia (sodium 118 mmol/L) manifesting as confusion and reduced consciousness. The biochemical findings confirm syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion: hypotonic hyponatraemia with inappropriately concentrated urine and elevated urine sodium. The euvolaemic state is highly suggestive of syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion, and normal thyroid function testing and normal cortisol exclude hypothyroidism and adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo factors contribute to syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion in this case: post-operative stress (which stimulates antidiuretic hormone release) and recent initiation of paroxetine, a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor known to cause syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion. The combination of these factors has led to excessive water retention despite normal sodium handling by the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous 3% hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct immediate management for severe symptomatic hyponatraemia. The presence of neurological symptoms (confusion, reduced Glasgow Coma Scale) indicates cerebral oedema requiring urgent but controlled sodium correction. The initial target is to raise serum sodium by 4-6 mmol/L in the first 4-6 hours to reverse symptoms, with careful monitoring to avoid osmotic demyelination syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction to 800mL/day\u003C/strong\u003E is the mainstay of syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion management in mild, asymptomatic cases. However, it is too slow for severe symptomatic hyponatraemia where immediate correction is needed to prevent seizures, coma, or death. Fluid restriction would be appropriate after initial stabilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous 0.9% normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E may paradoxically worsen hyponatraemia in syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion. Since the urine is more concentrated than normal saline (380 mOsm/kg vs 308 mOsm/kg), the kidneys will excrete the sodium while retaining free water, further diluting the serum sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium chloride tablets\u003C/strong\u003E are used in sodium-deficient states where there is true sodium loss. In syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion, the problem is water excess rather than sodium deficiency, making oral sodium supplementation ineffective and potentially harmful as it may worsen fluid retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if adrenal insufficiency were suspected. However, the normal morning cortisol, absence of hyperkalaemia or hypoglycaemia, and normal blood pressure make this diagnosis unlikely. The clinical picture is consistent with syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion from combined post-operative stress and selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe symptomatic hyponatraemia requires urgent correction with hypertonic saline to prevent neurological complications.","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion is diagnosed by hypotonic hyponatraemia, inappropriately concentrated urine, and euvolaemia.","Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors and post-operative stress are common precipitants of syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion."],"references":["Shannon G. Severe hyponatraemia: recognition and management. Aust Prescr. 2011;34(2):42\u201345. Available at: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/severe-hyponatraemia-recognition-and-management.html","Griffing GT. Addison disease workup: laboratory studies, imaging studies, other tests. Medscape. 2019. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116467-workup","Simon EE. Hyponatremia: practice essentials, pathophysiology, epidemiology. Medscape. 2019. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/242166-overview","Yasir M, Mechanic OJ. Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH). StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2019. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1944"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T14:41:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T14:41:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"